Repeatability of a sexual signal trait

This first data set was extracted from a paper by Griffith and Sheldon (2001, Animal Behaviour 61: 987993), who measured the white forehead patch of 30 male collared flycatchers in two years on the Swedish island of Gotland. The patch is important in mate attraction, but varies in size from year to year. Our goal here will be to estimate the repeatability of patch length (mm). The data are here.

  1. Read and examine the data. Create a plot showing the pair of measurements for each individual flycatcher in the two years of study. Is there evidence of measurement variability between years?

Fit a linear mixed-effects model

  1. Fit a linear mixed-effects model to the data, treating the individual birds as the random groups. Note: The two measurements on each bird were taken in successive years of the study. For simplicity here, do not include year in the model.
m1 <- lmer(patch ~ 1 +(1|bird), data = flycatcher)
plot(m1)

qqnorm(resid(m1))
qqline(resid(m1))

#The two sources of random variation are the individual bird and the leftover error (residuals). The fixed effects give the estimates(mean) of the intercept(patch values).
  1. In the output, examine the standard deviations for the random effects. There should be two standard deviations: one for (Intercept) and one for Residual. This is because the mixed effects model has two sources of random variation: variation among repeat measurements within birds, and true variation among birds in their patch lengths. Which of these two sources corresponds to (Intercept) and which to Residual?
#Variation among repeat measurements within birds refers to the residual and true variation among birds in patch lengths corresponds with the intercept.

  1. Also examine the output for the fixed effect results. The only fixed effect in the model formula is the grand mean of all the patch length measurements. It is called (Intercept), but dont confuse with the intercept for the random effects. The fixed effect output gives you the estimate of the grand mean and a standard error for that estimate. Notice how the fixed effect output provides estimates of means, whereas the random effects output provides estimates of variances (or standard deviations).

  2. Extract the variance components from the fitted model and estimate the repeatability of patch length from year to year*.

VarCorr(m1)

#The source of variation among measurements within the individual birds could be due to measurement(human error) and also to growth of the bird (due to the year time difference in measuring).
  1. Produce a plot of residuals against fitted values. Notice anything odd? There seems to be a slightly positive trend. This isnt a mistake, but results from shrinkage of the best linear unbiased predictors (BLUPs).
e1=resid(m1)
f1=fitted(m1)
qplot(x=f1,y=e1)+geom_point()+geom_hline(yintercept=0)

Example 2 - Goldies vision

Cronly-Dillon and Muntz (1965; J. Exp. Biol 42: 481-493) used the optomotor response to measure color vision in the goldfish. We looked at these data breifly today in lecture. Here we will fit a model to the data and include the full set of wavelengths tested. Each of 5 fish was tested at all the wavelengths in random order. A large value of sensitivity indicates that the fish can detect a low light intensity. An important feature of the optomotor response is that fish dont habituate, and it is unlikely that a measurement of visual sensitivity under one wavelength would carry over and have an effect on later measurements at another wavelength.

  1. Read and examine the data. Create a graphic to visually explore the data. What type of experimental design was used? This will determine the linear mixed model to use when fitting the data.
gold<-read.csv("~/GitHub/goldfish.csv",stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
head(gold)
ggplot(gold,aes(x=wavelength,y=sensitivity,colour=fish))+geom_jitter(size=2,height=.5,width=0.1,alpha=0.5)

#The type of experimental design is repeated measures.

Fit a linear mixed-effects model

  1. Fit a linear mixed-effects model to the data. Note: R will give you the message: boundary (singular) fit. What do you think this means? The reason will become clearer as we go along but for now, proceed as though all is well.
m2 <- lmer(sensitivity ~ wavelength + (1 | fish),data = gold)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
plot(m2)

qqnorm(resid(m2))
qqline(resid(m2))

  1. Plot the fitted (predicted) values. The difference between the predicted and observed values for each fish represent the residuals.
betas=fixef(m2)
X_mat=model.matrix(m2)
fit_vals=X_mat%*%betas

library(broom.mixed)
x <- augment(m2)
x <- transform(x,fish=reorder(fish,X=.resid,FUN=mean,sort=sort))

  1. Inspect the output for the random effects. Once again we have two sources of random error in our mixed effects model. What are they? Which of them corresponds to the (Intercept) and which to the Residual in the output?
#The sources of random error are sensitivity measurements between the groups of fish(intercept) and measurement variations within the individual fish across different wavelengths (residual).

Notice that the estimated standard deviation for one of the sources of variation is very small (or missing) in this data set. This is the reason behind the boundary (singular) fit message. It is unlikely that the variance among fish really is zero, but this data set is very small and low variance estimates can occur because of sampling error. Note ignoring this error is not ideal/wrong, but dont worry about it for now. We will revisit this and discuss possible solutions later.
